<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=beastlordbalance&message.id=2320#M2320">4</a> of 118
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 2045 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			The healing staying on par with rangers part is important, if you look at the Rangers section:<br> b.  We will be boosting your healing ability, particularly at the top end of the game.<br><br>--<br><br>The pet healing problem is a little more complex than just the healing spell.  The reason the healing spell would have to be super-fast cast for us to even consider using it, is because our pet dies too fast in many places.  This also isn't a simple problem, because there is a large range of difficulties a lvl 70 beastlord might be playing in.<br><br>For example, if I'm fighting blue mobs in an easier DoN mission, my pet can distract an add for a short time, and an 8 second heal might actually land before it dies (assuming I start casting it early).  On the other hand, if I'm in Riftseekers and a mob is on my pet, sometimes there's not even time to react and use our instant cast pet heal aa before the pet dies.  With high end gear we take hits way better than our pet does, so it's more effecient to take the hits ourself.<br><br>Long casting time pet heals hurt us in other ways that are unrelated to the pet's health.  We aren't doing melee damage while casting the heal.  Also mana used to heal our pet means less mana to use for healing, nuking, and debuffing.<br><br>--<br><br>I think the proposed solution to our slows will be useful in many group and solo situations, particularyly when we're the only slower in a group.  However, they do not address our role of debuffing on raids, or in groups that contain a shaman or enchanter.<br><br>I slow on raids all the time, usually casting it before a mob even makes it to the raid.  A majority of the time though, my slow only lasts 2-3 seconds before it has been overriden by a shaman slow.<br><br>In groups with an enchanter/shaman, the same thing happens: I might pull with slow as a mob comes in, but all my effort becomes pointless a few seconds later when the enchanter overrides it.<br><br>I can think of two reasonable ways giving us a reasonable debuffing role:<br><br>1:<br>Add a unique beastlord debuff that doesn't have stacking problems with enchanter/shaman debuffs.  This could be something like a small accuracy debuff, or any number of things.<br><br>2:<br>A little more complex, but a way to allow both shaman and beastlord to slow a mob.<br><br>Each of our slow spells might be made up of two slow components that stack (will refer to as part A and part B).  Shaman's 75% slow might be made up of 60% part A, and 15% part B.  Beastlords 65% slow could then be made up of 40% part A and 25% part B.  The best % from each part takes hold independantly.<br><br>If this were the case, then if a shaman slows a mob, it will still be 75% (60% + 15%) like before.  If a beastlord then slows the same mob, part A would not take hold, but part B would override it.  The slow on the mob would then be 85% (60% from shaman + 25% from beastlord).
								<p><div style="width: 100%; height: 120; overflow: hidden;">
								
							<a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=427689">Rarrum, The Kitty of Doom</a><br><br>Pravus Mortis - Druzzil Ro
							</div>
								
