		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			Sure a beastlord/mage/necro can keep a pet alive on higher end raid encounters.  I can use feral guard, growl of the panther, pet mend, and a light healing spell and keep the pet up.  But to do this on some encoutner that has to be just about everything the beastlord/mage/necro does.  Now I would suggest as a fix making pet only spells work like mend companion and hobble of spirits where the pet does not need to be the target to recieve the effect.  also reducing the cast time on these to almost nothing (.5 seconds like growl perhaps) but increasing recast time would allow the beastlord/mage/necro to maintain there job on the raid (Mana battery, dps, whatever) while still keeping there pet alive.  <br><br>On the note of Growl.  I love the spell, but you should realy be able to use it while a pet is not around.  I doesn't stack with our damage modifying discs/aa's and has deminished returns while a pet isn't out, but it would give us something on encounters where if we tried to keep our pet alive to use the effect of the spell we aren't realy dpsing the mob.<br><br>The resist modded slow will be nice as will the reduced agro.<br><br>I would suggest maybe adding a small resist mod to all anchient spells to give the person a bit more than a spell that will be outdated with the next spell set that is brought forth.  If anchient frozen chaos was less resistable than Glacier Spear then there would be some desireability to get the more difficult to find spell over the more common one even with the lower total damage done.  I am not saying this should be a beastlord only change but a change in general to anchient spell design for detrimental spells.<br><br>Those are my oppinions and I am so happy monks are getting unnerfed.<br><br>-Snowmeow-	
